fields.descriptive_line: Marquetry ceiling from the Palacio de Altamira in Torrijos (near Toledo)
fields.physical_description: Marquetry ceiling decorated with an all-over framework of geometric starburst designs. Octagonal and arranged in three zones radiating from a muqarnas boss at the centre. A more 'Gothic' section with four squinches provides the transition from the square hall to the octagonal dome.
fields.materials_techniques: Pine wood, covered with gesso, painted and gilt
fields.bibliography: M. Rosser-Owen. Islamic Arts from Spain (London: V&A Publishing, 2010), p. 86.
fields.history_note: One of four surviving ceilings from the Palacio de Altamira in Torrijos, near Toledo, built for Guitiérre de Cárdenas, chamberlain to Isabella the Catholic, and his wife Teresa Enríquez, the queen's cousin. A good example of the taste for Mudéjar styles among the Spanish elite at the turn of the fifteenth and sixteenth centuries. The squinches contain the coats of arms of the Cárdenas and Enríquez families. The construction, design and decoration show continuation from the marquetry ceilings created for the Alhambra a century and a half before. (M. Rosser-Owen, 2010).
